\f1\b0\fs38 \cf2 {\listtext	\'95	}6 garlic cloves, chopped\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/4 cup fresh ginger, peeled and chopped\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup vegetable oil\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup tahini (sesame paste)\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup smooth peanut butter\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup good soy sauce\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/4 cup dry sherry\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/4 cup sherry vinegar\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/4 cup honey\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 teaspoon hot chili oil\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 tablespoons dark sesame oil\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/8 teaspoon ground cayenne pepper\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 pound spaghetti\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 red bell pepper, julienned\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 yellow bell pepper, julienned\
{\listtext	\'95	}4 scallions, sliced diagonally (white and green parts)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs48 \cf2 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa180\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs38 \cf2 Place the garlic and ginger in a food processor fitted with a steel blade. Add the vegetable oil, tahini, peanut butter, soy sauce, sherry, sherry vinegar, honey, chili oil, sesame oil, and ground peppers. Puree the sauce.\
Add a splash of oil to a large pot of boiling salted water and cook the spaghetti al dente. Drain the pasta in a colander, place it in a large bowl, and while still warm, toss with 3/4 of the sauce. Add the red and yellow bell peppers and scallions; toss well. Serve warm or at room temperature. The remaining sauce may be added, as needed, to moisten the pasta.\
